      <accessrestrict id="aspace_arest">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>Easley's compositions are open to researchers by appointment. There are no restricted materials in the collection. Please contact the <ref actuate="onrequest"
                 href="http://www.library.yale.edu/musiclib"
                 show="new">Special Collections staff</ref> to schedule an appointment.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_d1e217">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>The collection was established in the Music Library of Yale University by Dorothy Easley in 1974.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <userestrict id="aspace_urest">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>The collection is the physical property of the Irving S. Gilmore Music Library of Yale University. Copyrights belong to the composers and authors, or their legal heirs and assigns.</p>  
      </userestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_cite">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Misc. Ms. 52, Selected Compositions of Peter Easley in the Irving S. Gilmore Music Library of Yale University.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <arrangement id="aspace_arr1">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Arranged in alphabetical order by title.</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_sc">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection contains manuscript scores and parts for 11 musical compositions by Peter Easley. Among the works included are concertos for piano and cello, sonatas for piano and violin, 2 symphonies, a string quartet, and settings for voice of texts by Edna St. Vincent Millay and Paul Verlaine. Some of the manuscripts are stored in rolls rather than flat, and some are negative stencils.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
      <bioghist id="aspace_bh1">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Peter Easley, whose real name was Ronald Merl Easley, Jr., was born in 1927 in Salem, Massachusetts. He attended Yale College from 1944 to 1946, completing two semesters, and finished his schooling at the University of New Mexico. He died in 1974.</p>  
      </bioghist>
